# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ambassador-clipper
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Named in honour of Adelaide of Saxe-Meiningen, wife of King William IV, the city was founded in 1836 as the planned capital for a freely settled British colony in Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Colonel William Light, one of Adelaide's founding fathers, designed the city centre and chose its location close to the River Torrens.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Light's design, now listed as national heritage, set out the city centre in a grid layout known as "Light's Vision", interspaced by wide boulevards and large public squares, and entirely surrounded by park lands.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Colonial Adelaide was noted for its leading examples of religious freedom and progressive political reforms and became known as the "City of Churches" due to its diversity of faiths.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] It was Australia's third-most populous city until the postwar era.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Today, Adelaide is one of Australia's most visited travel destinations and hosts many festivals and sporting events, such as the Adelaide 500, Tour Down Under, Gather Round, LIV Golf Adelaide, and the Adelaide Fringe, the world's second largest annual arts festival.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide also hosts men's tennis with an ATP 250 event and women's tennis with a WTA 500 event, and will also become the new host of the Australian MotoGP Grand Prix from 2027.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The city has also been renowned for its automotive industry, having been the original host of the Australian Grand Prix in the FIA Formula One World Championship from 1985 to 1995.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Other features include its food and wine industries, its coastline and hills, its large defence and manufacturing operations, and its emerging space sector, including the Australian Space Agency being headquartered there.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] With one of the world's largest foreign-born populations, Adelaide has consistently ranked within the top-ten most liveable cities globally for much of the 21st century, being named in 2021 the most liveable city in the country and third in the world.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Its aesthetic appeal has also been recognised by *Architectural Digest*, which ranked Adelaide as the most beautiful city in the world in 2024.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] As South Australia's government and commercial centre, Adelaide is the site of many governmental and financial institutions.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Most of these are concentrated in the central business district along the cultural boulevards of North Terrace and King William Street.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has also been classed as a Gamma + level global city as categorised by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network, with the city further linking economic regions to the worldwide economy.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is connected by extensive bus, train and tram networks, all of which are operated by Adelaide Metro, with its main railway terminus at the Adelaide railway station.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The city is also served by Adelaide Airport and Port Adelaide, both of which are among the busiest airports and seaports in Australia, respectively.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The amount of time Aboriginal people have been living in the area around modern-day Adelaide has been described as "millennia", "tens of thousands of years", "thousands of generations", or "innumerable generations".
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] At Hallett Cove Conservation Park in Adelaide's southern suburbs, archaeological evidence of Aboriginal culture has been found dating back 40,000 years.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The area was originally inhabited by the Kaurna people, one of many Aboriginal tribes in South Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The city and parklands area also known as *Tarndanyangga* *Tandanya*, *Tarndanya* or *Tarntanya*.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The name means 'male red kangaroo rock', referring to a rock formation on the site that has now been destroyed.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The surrounding area was an open, grassy plain with patches of trees and shrubs, which had been managed by hundreds of generations.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Kaurna country encompassed the plains stretching north and south of Tarntanya, as well as the wooded foothills of the Mt Lofty Ranges.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The River Torrens was known as the Karrawirra Pari (Red Gum forest river).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] About 300 Kaurna populated the Adelaide area, and were referred to by the settlers as the Cowandilla.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The more than 20 local clans across the plain lived seminomadic lives, with extensive mound settlements where huts were built repeatedly over centuries and a complex social structure, including a class of sorcerers separated from regular society.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Within a few decades of European settlement of South Australia, Kaurna culture was almost completely lost, with the last speaker of Kaurna language having died in 1929.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Extensive documentation by early missionaries and other researchers has enabled a modern revival of both, which has included a commitment by local and state governments to rename or include Kaurna names for many local places.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Based on the ideas of Edward Gibbon Wakefield about colonial reform, Robert Gouger petitioned the British government to create a new colony in Australia, resulting in the passage of the South Australia Act 1834.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Physical establishment of the colony began with the arrival of the first British colonisers in February 1836, followed by the commencement of colonial government in South Australia on 28 December 1836.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Proclaimed by the governor near The Old Gum Tree in what is now the suburb of Glenelg North, this day is annually commemorated in South Australia as Proclamation Day.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Named for Queen Adelaide, the site of the colony's capital was surveyed and laid out by Colonel William Light, the first surveyor-general of South Australia, with his own original, unique and topographically sensitive design.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was established as a planned colony of free settlers, promising civil liberties and freedom from religious persecution, based upon the ideas of Edward Gibbon Wakefield.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Wakefield had read accounts of Australian settlement while in prison in London for attempting to abduct an heiress, and realised that the eastern colonies suffered from a lack of available labour, due to the practice of giving land grants to all arrivals.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Wakefield's idea was for the Government to survey and sell the land at a rate that would maintain land values high enough to be unaffordable for labourers and journeymen.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Funds raised from the sale of land were to be used to bring out working-class emigrants, who would have to work hard for the monied settlers to ever afford their own land.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] As a result of this policy, Adelaide does not share the convict settlement history of other Australian cities like Sydney, Brisbane and Hobart.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] As it was believed that in a colony of free settlers there would be little crime, no provision was made for a gaol in Colonel Light's 1837 plan.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] But by mid-1837 the *South Australian Register* was warning of escaped convicts from New South Wales and tenders for a temporary gaol were sought.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Following a burglary, a murder, and two attempted murders in Adelaide during March 1838, Governor Hindmarsh created the South Australian Police Force (now the South Australia Police) in April 1838 under 21-year-old Henry Inman.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The first sheriff, Samuel Smart, was wounded during a robbery, and on 2 May 1838 one of the offenders, Michael Magee, became the first person to be hanged in South Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] William Baker Ashton was appointed governor of the temporary gaol in 1839, and in 1840 George Strickland Kingston was commissioned to design Adelaide's new gaol.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Construction of Adelaide Gaol commenced in 1841.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's early history was marked by economic uncertainty and questionable leadership.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The first governor of South Australia, John Hindmarsh, clashed frequently with others, in particular the Resident Commissioner, James Hurtle Fisher.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The rural area surrounding Adelaide was surveyed by Light in preparation to sell a total of over 405 km2 (156 sq mi) of land.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's early economy started to get on its feet in 1838 with the arrival of livestock from Victoria, New South Wales and Tasmania.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Wool production provided an early basis for the South Australian economy.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] By 1860, wheat farms had been established from Encounter Bay in the south to Clare in the north.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] He was criticised for his response to the Maria massacre.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Gawler was recalled and replaced by George Edward Grey in 1841.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Grey slashed public expenditure against heavy opposition, although its impact was negligible at this point: silver was discovered in Glen Osmond that year, agriculture was well underway, and other mines sprung up all over the state, aiding Adelaide's commercial development.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The city exported meat, wool, wine, fruit and wheat by the time Grey left in 1845, contrasting with a low point in 1842 when one-third of Adelaide houses were abandoned.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Trade links with the rest of the Australian states were established after the Murray River was successfully navigated in 1853 by Francis Cadell, an Adelaide resident.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] South Australia became a self-governing colony in 1856 with the ratification of a new constitution by the British parliament.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Secret ballots were introduced, and a bicameral parliament was elected on 9 March 1857, by which time 109,917 people lived in the province.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In 1860, the Thorndon Park reservoir was opened, providing an alternative water source to the now turbid River Torrens.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Gas street lighting was implemented in 1867, the University of Adelaide was founded in 1874, the South Australian Art Gallery opened in 1881 and the Happy Valley Reservoir opened in 1896.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In the 1890s Australia was affected by a severe economic depression, ending a hectic era of land booms and tumultuous expansionism.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Financial institutions in Melbourne and banks in Sydney closed.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The national fertility rate fell and immigration was reduced to a trickle.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The value of South Australia's exports nearly halved.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Drought and poor harvests from 1884 compounded the problems, with some families leaving for Western Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was not as badly hit as the larger gold-rush cities of Sydney and Melbourne, and silver and lead discoveries at Broken Hill provided some relief.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Only one year of deficit was recorded, but the price paid was retrenchments and lean public spending.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Wine and copper were the only industries not to suffer a downturn.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was Australia's third largest city for most of the 20th century.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Electric street lighting was introduced in 1900 and electric trams were transporting passengers in 1909.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] 28,000 men were sent to fight in World War I.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Crowley examined the reports of visitors in the early 20th century, noting that "many visitors to Adelaide admired the foresighted planning of its founders", as well as pondering the riches of the young city.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide enjoyed a postwar boom, entering a time of relative prosperity.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Its population grew, and it became the third most populous metropolitan area in the country, after Sydney and Melbourne.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Its prosperity was short-lived, with the return of droughts and the Great Depression of the 1930s.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] It later returned to fortune under strong government leadership.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Secondary industries helped reduce the state's dependence on primary industries.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] World War II brought industrial stimulus and diversification to Adelaide under the Playford Government, which advocated Adelaide as a safe place for manufacturing due to its less vulnerable location.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Shipbuilding was expanded at the nearby port of Whyalla.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The South Australian Government in this period built on former wartime manufacturing industries but neglected cultural facilities which meant South Australia's economy lagged behind.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] International manufacturers like Holden and Chrysler made use of these factories around the Adelaide area in suburbs like Elizabeth, completing its transformation from an agricultural service centre to a 20th-century motor city.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Mannum–Adelaide pipeline brought River Murray water to Adelaide in 1955 and an airport opened at West Beach in 1955.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Flinders University and the Flinders Medical Centre were established in the 1960s at Bedford Park, south of the city.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Today, Flinders Medical Centre is one of the largest teaching hospitals in South Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In the post-war years around the early 1960s, Adelaide was surpassed by Brisbane as Australia's third largest city.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Dunstan Governments of the 1970s saw something of an Adelaide "cultural revival", establishing a wide array of social reforms.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The city became noted for its progressivism as South Australia became the first Australian state or territory to decriminalise homosexuality between consenting adults in 1975.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide became a centre for the arts, building upon the biennial "Adelaide Festival of Arts" that commenced in 1960.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The State Bank collapsed in 1991 during an economic recession.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The effects lasted until 2004, when Standard & Poor's reinstated South Australia's AAA credit rating.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's tallest building, completed in 2020, is called the Adelaidean and is located at 11 Frome Street.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In the early years of the 21st century, a significant increase in the state government's spending on Adelaide's infrastructure occurred.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Rann government invested A$535 million in a major upgrade of the Adelaide Oval to enable Australian Football League to be played in the city centre and more than A$2 billion to build a new Royal Adelaide Hospital on land adjacent to the Adelaide Railway Station.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Glenelg tramline was extended through the city to Hindmarsh down to East Terrace and the suburban railway line extended south to Seaford.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Following a period of stagnation in the 1990s and 2000s, Adelaide began several major developments and redevelopments.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Convention Centre was redeveloped and expanded at a cost of A$350 million beginning in 2012.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The government invested more than A$2 billion to build a desalination plant, powered by renewable energy, as an "insurance policy" against droughts affecting Adelaide's water supply.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Festival, Fringe, and Womadelaide became annual events.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is north of the Fleurieu Peninsula, on the Adelaide Plains between the Gulf St Vincent and the relatively low-lying Mount Lofty Ranges (Mount Lofty, the highest point, is 710 metres above sea level).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The city stretches 20 km (12 mi) from the coast to the foothills, and 90 km (56 mi) from Gawler at its northern extent to Sellicks Beach in the south.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The city sits at an average elevation of 50 metres (160 ft) above sea level.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Mount Lofty, east of the Adelaide metropolitan region in the Adelaide Hills at an elevation of 727 metres (2,385 ft), is the tallest point of the city and in the state south of Burra.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The city borders the Temperate Grassland of South Australia in the east, an endangered vegetation community.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Much of Adelaide was bushland before British settlement, with some variation – sandhills, swamps and marshlands were prevalent around the coast.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The loss of the sandhills to urban development had a particularly destructive effect on the coastline due to erosion.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Where practical, the government has implemented programs to rebuild and vegetate sandhills at several of Adelaide's beachside suburbs.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Tennyson Dunes is the largest contiguous, tertiary dune system contained entirely within Metropolitan Adelaide, providing refuge for a variety of remnant species formerly found along the entire coastline.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Much of the original vegetation has been cleared with what is left to be found in reserves such as the Cleland National Park and Belair National Park.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] A number of creeks and rivers flow through the Adelaide region.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The largest are the Torrens and Onkaparinga catchments.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide relies on its many reservoirs for water supply with the Happy Valley Reservoir supplying around 40% and the much larger Mount Bold Reservoir 10% of Adelaide's domestic requirements respectively.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide and its surrounding area is one of the most seismically active regions in Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] On 1 March 1954 at 3:40 am Adelaide experienced its largest recorded earthquake to date, with the epicentre 12 km from the city centre at Darlington, and a reported magnitude of 5.6.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Most of the Adelaide metropolitan area lies in the downthrown St Vincent Basin and its embayments, including the Adelaide Plains Sub-basin, and the Golden Grove, Noarlunga and Willunga Embayments.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] These basins contain deposits of Tertiary marine and non-marine sands and limestones, which form important aquifers.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is a planned city, designed by the first Surveyor-General of South Australia, Colonel William Light.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] His plan, sometimes referred to as "Light's Vision" (also the name of a statue of him on Montefiore Hill), arranged Adelaide in a grid, with five squares in the Adelaide city centre and a ring of parks, known as the Adelaide Parklands, surrounding it.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Light's selection of the location for the city was initially unpopular with the early settlers, as well as South Australia's first governor, John Hindmarsh, due to its distance from the harbour at Port Adelaide, and the lack of fresh water there.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Light successfully persisted with his choice of location against this initial opposition.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The benefits of Light's design are numerous: Adelaide has had wide multi-lane roads from its beginning, an easily navigable cardinal direction grid layout and an expansive green ring around the city centre.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] There are two sets of ring roads in Adelaide that have resulted from the original design.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The inner ring route (A21) borders the parklands, and the outer route (A3/A13/A16/A17) completely bypasses the inner city via (in clockwise order) Grand Junction Road, Hampstead Road, Ascot Avenue, Portrush Road, Cross Road and South Road.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Suburban expansion has to some extent outgrown Light's original plan.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Numerous former outlying villages and "country towns", as well as the satellite city of Elizabeth, have been enveloped by its suburban sprawl.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Expanding developments in the Adelaide Hills region led to the construction of the South Eastern Freeway to cope with growth, which has subsequently led to new developments and further improvements to that transport corridor.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Similarly, the booming development in Adelaide's South led to the construction of the Southern Expressway.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] New roads are not the only transport infrastructure developed to cope with the urban growth.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The O-Bahn Busway and Adelaide Metro are examples of a unique solution to Tea Tree Gully's transport woes in the 1980s.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The development of the nearby suburb of Golden Grove in the late 1980s followed a planned approach to urban growth.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In the 1960s, a Metropolitan Adelaide Transport Study Plan was proposed to cater for the future growth of the city.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The plan involved the construction of freeways, expressways and the upgrade of certain aspects of the public transport system.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The then premier Steele Hall approved many parts of the plan and the government went as far as purchasing land for the project.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The later Labor government elected under Don Dunstan shelved the plan, but allowed the purchased land to remain vacant, should the future need for freeways arise.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In 1980, the Liberal party won government and premier David Tonkin committed his government to selling off the land acquired for the MATS plan, ensuring that even when needs changed, the construction of most MATS-proposed freeways would be impractical.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Some parts of this land have been used for transport, (e.g. the O-Bahn Busway and Southern Expressway), while most has been progressively subdivided for residential use.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In 2008, the SA Government announced plans for a network of transport-oriented developments across the Adelaide metropolitan area and purchased a 10 hectare industrial site at Bowden for $52.5 million as the first of these developments.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Historically, Adelaide's suburban residential areas have been characterised by single-storey detached houses built on 1,000-square-metre (1⁄4-acre) blocks.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] A relative lack of suitable, locally available timber for construction purposes led to the early development of a brick-making industry, as well as the use of stone, for houses and other buildings.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] By 1891, 68% of houses were built of stone, 15% of timber, and 10% of brick, with brick also being widely used in stone houses for quoins, door and window surrounds, and chimneys and fireplaces.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] There is a wide variety in the styles of these houses.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Until the 1960s, most of the more substantial houses were built of red brick, though many front walls were of ornamental stone.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Then cream bricks became fashionable, and in the 1970s, deep red and brown bricks became popular.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Until the 1970s, roofs tended to be clad with (painted) corrugated iron or cement or clay tiles, usually red "terracotta".
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Since then, Colorbond corrugated steel has dominated.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Up to the 1970s, most houses were of "double brick" construction on concrete footings, with timber floors laid on joists supported by "dwarf walls".
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The use of precast concrete panels for floor and wall construction has also increased.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In addition to this, a significant factor in Adelaide's suburban history is the role of the South Australian Housing Trust.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has a hot-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*) under the Köppen climate classification.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The city has hot, dry summers and cool winters with moderate rainfall.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Most rain falls in the winter months, leading to the suggestion that the climate be classified as a "cold monsoon".
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Rainfall is unreliable, light and infrequent throughout summer, although heavy falls can occur.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The winter has fairly reliable rainfall with June being the wettest month of the year, averaging around 80 mm.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Frosts are occasional, with the most notable occurrences in 1908 and 1982.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is a windy city with significant wind chill in winter, which makes the temperature seem colder than it actually is.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Snowfall in the metropolitan area is extremely rare, although light and sporadic falls in the nearby hills and at Mount Lofty occur during winter.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Dewpoints in the summer typically range from 8 to 10 °C (46 to 50 °F).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] There are usually several days in summer where the temperature reaches 40.0 °C (104.0 °F) or above.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] While conditions vary from year-to-year, a warming trend has been increasing in recent years, and with drought conditions experienced in SA in 2024−25, Adelaide has had to rely on desalination to augment its water supply.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The city features 90.6 clear days annually.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The average sea temperature ranges from 13.7 °C (56.7 °F) in August to 21.2 °C (70.2 °F) in February.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was consistently ranked in the world's 10 most liveable cities through the 2010s by The Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In June 2021, *The Economist* ranked Adelaide the third most liveable city in the world, behind Auckland and Osaka.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In June 2023, Adelaide was ranked the twelfth most liveable city in the world by the Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In December 2021, Adelaide was named the world's second National Park City, after the state government had lobbied for this title.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] It was ranked the most liveable city in Australia by the Property Council of Australia, based on surveys of residents' views of their own city, between 2010 and 2013, dropping to second place in 2014.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide, as the capital of South Australia, is the seat of the Government of South Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The bicameral Parliament of South Australia consists of the lower house known as the House of Assembly and the upper house known as the Legislative Council.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] General elections are held every four years, the last being the 2022 South Australian state election.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] As Adelaide is South Australia's capital and most populous city, the State Government co-operates extensively with the City of Adelaide.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In 2006, the Ministry for the City of Adelaide was created to facilitate the State Government's collaboration with the Adelaide City Council and the Lord Mayor to improve Adelaide's image.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The State Parliament's Capital City Committee is also involved in the governance of the City of Adelaide, being primarily concerned with the planning of Adelaide's urban development and growth.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Reflecting South Australia's status as Australia's most centralised state, Adelaide elects a substantial majority of the South Australian House of Assembly.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Of the 47 seats in the chamber, 34 seats (three-quarters of the legislature) are based in Adelaide, and two rural seats include Adelaide suburbs.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide metropolitan area is divided between nineteen local government areas.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] At its centre, the City of Adelaide administers the Adelaide city centre, North Adelaide, and the surrounding Adelaide Parklands.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] It is the oldest municipal authority in Australia and was established in 1840, when Adelaide and Australia's first mayor, James Hurtle Fisher, was elected.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] From 1919 onwards, the city has had a Lord Mayor, the current being Lord Mayor *The Right Honourable* Jane Lomax-Smith.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's inhabitants are known as Adelaideans.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Compared with Australia's other state capitals, Adelaide is growing at a rate similar to Sydney and Hobart (see List of cities in Australia by population).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In 2024, it had a metropolitan population (including suburbs) of 1,469,163, making it Australia's fifth-largest city.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] 77% of the population of South Australia are residents of the Adelaide metropolitan area, making South Australia one of the most centralised states.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Major areas of population growth in recent years have been in outer suburbs such as Mawson Lakes and Golden Grove.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's inhabitants occupy 366,912 houses, 57,695 semi-detached, row terrace or town houses and 49,413 flats, units or apartments.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] About one sixth (17.1%) of the population had university qualifications.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The number of Adelaideans with vocational qualifications (such as tradespersons) fell from 62.1% of the labour force in the 1991 census to 52.4% in the 2001 census.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is aging more rapidly than other Australian capital cities.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] More than a quarter (27.5%) of Adelaide's population is aged 55 years or older, in comparison to the national average of 25.6%.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has the lowest number of children (under-15-year-olds), who comprised 17.7% of the population, compared to the national average of 19.3%.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Overseas-born Adelaideans composed 31.3% of the total population at the 2021 census.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The five largest groups of overseas-born were from England (5.7%), India (3.1%), Mainland China (1.8%), Vietnam (1.2%) and Italy (1.1%).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Suburbs including Newton, Payneham and Campbelltown in the east and Torrensville, West Lakes and Fulham to the west, have large Greek and Italian communities.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Italian consulate is located in the western suburb of Hindmarsh.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Large Vietnamese populations are settled in the north-western suburbs of Woodville, Kilkenny, Pennington, Mansfield Park and Athol Park and also Parafield Gardens and Pooraka in Adelaide's north.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Migrants from India and Sri Lanka have settled into inner suburban areas of Adelaide including the inner northern suburbs of Blair Athol, Kilburn and Enfield and the inner southern suburbs of Plympton, Park Holme and Kurralta Park.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Suburbs such as Para Hills, Salisbury, Ingle Farm and Blair Athol in the north and Findon, West Croydon and Seaton and other Western suburbs have sizeable Afghan communities.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Chinese migrants favour settling in the eastern and north eastern suburbs including Kensington Gardens, Greenacres, Modbury and Golden Grove.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Mawson Lakes has a large international student population, due to its proximity to the University of South Australia campus.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] At the 2021 census, 1.7% of Adelaide's population identified as being Indigenous — Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] At the 2016 census, 75.4% of the population spoke English at home.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The other languages most commonly spoken at home were Italian (2.1%), Standard Mandarin (2.1%), Greek (1.7%) Vietnamese (1.4%), and Cantonese (0.7%).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Kaurna language, spoken by the area's original inhabitants, had no living speakers in the middle of the 20th century, but since the 1990s there has been a sustained revival effort from academics and Kaurna elders.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was founded on a vision of religious tolerance that attracted a wide variety of religious practitioners.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] This led to it being known as *The City of Churches*.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] But approximately 28% of the population expressed no religious affiliation in the 2011 Census, compared with the national average of 22.3%, making Adelaide one of Australia's least religious cities.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] According to 2021 census, 39.8% of the population of Adelaide identify as Christian, with the largest denominations being Catholic (16.4%), Anglican (7.0%), Uniting Church (3.9%) and Greek Orthodox (2.4%).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Non-Christian faith communities, representing 9.5% from Adelaide's population, include Islam (2.8%), Hinduism (2.7%) and Buddhism (2.3%).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Jewish community of the city dates back to 1840.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Eight years later, 58 Jews lived in the city.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] A synagogue was built in 1871, when 435 Jews lived in the city.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Many took part in the city councils, such as Judah Moss Solomon (1852–66).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Three Jews have been elected to the position of city mayor.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In 1968, the Jewish population of Adelaide numbered about 1,200; in 2001, according to the Australian census, 979 persons declared themselves to be Jewish by religion.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In 2011, over 1,000 Jews were living in the city, served by an Orthodox synagogue, Adelaide Hebrew Congregation and a Reform synagogue, **Beit Shalom**, in addition to a virtual Jewish museum.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Massada College, a Jewish day school opened in the city in 1976 and closed in 2011.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Holocaust Museum and Andrew Steiner Education Centre opened in 2020.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The "Afghan" community in Australia first became established in the 1860s when camels and their Pathan, Punjabi, Baluchi and Sindhi handlers began to be used to open up settlement in the continent's arid interior.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Until eventually superseded by the advent of the railways and motor vehicles, camels played an invaluable economic and social role in transporting heavy loads of goods to and from isolated settlements and mines.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] This is acknowledged by the name of The Ghan, the passenger train operating between Adelaide, Alice Springs, and Darwin.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Central Adelaide Mosque is regarded as Australia's oldest permanent mosque; an earlier mosque at Marree in northern South Australia, dating from 1861 to 1862 and subsequently abandoned or demolished, has now been rebuilt.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] South Australia's largest employment sectors are health care and social assistance, surpassing manufacturing in SA as the largest employer since 2006–07.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In 2009–10, manufacturing in SA had average annual employment of 83,700 persons compared with 103,300 for health care and social assistance.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Health care and social assistance represented nearly 13% of the state average annual employment.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Hills wine region is an iconic and viable economic region for both the state and country in terms of wine production and sale.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The retail trade is the second largest employer in SA (2009–10), with over 91,900 jobs, and 12 per cent of the state workforce.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Manufacturing, defence technology, high-tech electronic systems and research, commodity export and corresponding service industries all play a role in the SA economy.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Almost half of all cars produced in Australia were made in Adelaide at the Holden Elizabeth Plant in Elizabeth.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The site ceased operating in November 2017.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The collapse of the State Bank in 1992 resulted in large levels of state public debt (as much as A$4 billion).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The collapse meant that successive governments enacted lean budgets, cutting spending, which was a setback to the further economic development of the city and state.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] As of January 2026, the government has an AA+ credit rating.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The global media conglomerate News Corporation was founded in, and until 2004 incorporated in, Adelaide, and the city is still considered the Corporation's "spiritual" home by its founder, Rupert Murdoch.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Australia's largest oil company, Santos, prominent South Australian brewery, Coopers, and national retailer Harris Scarfe also call Adelaide their home.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] In 2018, at which time more than 80 organisations employed 800 people in the space sector in South Australia, Adelaide was chosen for the headquarters of a new Australian Space Agency.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] It is working to triple the size of the Australian space industry and create 20,000 new jobs by 2030.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is home to a large proportion of Australia's defence industries, which contribute over A$1 billion to South Australia's Gross State Product.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Others, such as Saab Systems and Raytheon, are in or near Technology Park.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] ASC Pty Ltd, is based in the industrial suburb of Osborne and is also a part of Technology Park.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] South Australia was charged with constructing Australia's *Collins*-class submarines and more recently the A$6 billion contract to construct the Royal Australian Navy's new air-warfare destroyers.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] As of November 2015, Greater Adelaide had an unemployment rate of 7.4% with a youth unemployment rate of 15%.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The median weekly individual income for people aged 15 years and over was $447 per week in 2006, compared with $466 nationally.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The median family income was $1,137 per week, compared with $1,171 nationally.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's housing and living costs are substantially lower than that of other Australian cities, with housing being notably cheaper.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The median Adelaide house price is half that of Sydney and two-thirds that of Melbourne.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The three-month trend unemployment rate to March 2007 was 6.2%.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] The Northern suburbs' unemployment rate is disproportionately higher than the other regions of Adelaide at 8.3%, while the East and South are lower than the Adelaide average at 4.9% and 5.0% respectively.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Over the decade March 2001 – March 2010, Metropolitan Adelaide median house prices approximately tripled.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] 11%p.a. compounding) In the five years March 2007 – March 2012, prices increased by approx.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] March 2012 – March 2017 saw a further increase of 19% – approx.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] no longer release a median house price for the Adelaide Metropolitan area, so figures retrieved are from Dept of the Premier and Cabinet.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Each quarter, The Alternative and Direct Investment Securities Association (ADISA) publishes a list of median house sale prices by suburb and Local Government Area.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p01] Quarterly Reports for the last two years can be found on the REISA website.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Education forms an increasingly important part of the city's economy, with the South Australian Government and educational institutions attempting to position Adelaide as "Australia's education hub" and marketing it as a "Learning City".
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The number of international students studying in Adelaide has increased rapidly in recent years to 30,726 in 2015, of which 1,824 were secondary school students.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is the birthplace of three Nobel laureates, more than any other Australian city: physicist William Lawrence Bragg and pathologists Howard Florey and Robin Warren, all of whom completed secondary and tertiary education at St Peter's College and the University of Adelaide.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is also the hometown of mathematician Terence Tao.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] There are two systems of primary and secondary schools, a public system operated by the South Australian Government's Department for Education, and a private system of independent and Catholic schools.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] South Australian schools provide education under the Australian Curriculum for reception to Year 10 students.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In Years 10 to 12, students study for the South Australian Certificate of Education (SACE).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] They have the option of incorporating vocational education and training (VET) courses or a flexible learning option (FLO).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] South Australia also has 24 schools that use International Baccalaureate programs as an alternative to the Australian Curriculum or SACE.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] These programs include the IB Primary Years Programme, the IB Middle Years Programme, and the IB Diploma Programme.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] For South Australian students who cannot attend a traditional school, including students who live in rural or remote areas, the state government runs the Open Access College (OAC), which provides virtual teaching.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The OAC has a campus in Marden which caters to students from reception to Year 12 and adults who haven't been able to complete their SACE.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Guardians are also able to apply for their child to be educated from home as long as they provide an education program which meets the same requirements as the Australian Curriculum as well as opportunities for social interaction.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] There are two public universities local to Adelaide, as well as one private university and three constituent colleges of foreign universities.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Flinders University of South Australia, Adelaide University and Torrens University Australia—part of the Laureate International Universities are based in Adelaide.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The University of Adelaide was ranked in the top 150 universities worldwide.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Flinders ranked in the top 250 and Uni SA in the top 300.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Torrens University Australia is part of an international network of over 70 higher education institutions in more than 30 countries worldwide.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide University is a recent amalgamation between the University of Adelaide and the University of South Australia, ranked in the top 150 globally and top 10 nationally.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Today, it stands as Australia's third-oldest university and a member of the leading "Group of Eight".
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The merged university has over 64,000 students and two main campuses on North Terrace, with many other campuses across South Australia, including in Whyalla and Mount Gambier.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The two universities had multiple proposals to merge into a single university.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] A proposal in 2018 failed due to uncertainty as to the new name and leadership of the merged university.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2022, the universities announced a new merger proposal, with the name and leadership issues settled and support from the South Australian government.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Flinders University, with 25,184 students, is based in the southern suburb of Bedford Park, alongside the Flinders Medical Centre, with additional campuses in neighbouring Tonsley and in Victoria Square in the city centre.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2024, the University of the Sunshine Coast opened a new campus in Adelaide where undergraduate and master's courses in ICT and business are offered.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide College of Divinity is at Brooklyn Park.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] There are several South Australian TAFE (Technical and Further Education) campuses in the metropolitan area that provide a range of vocational education and training.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide College of the Arts, as a school of TAFE SA, provides nationally recognised training in visual and performing arts.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Workers' Educational Association of South Australia (WEA-SA) is an independent not-for-profit adult education organisation based in Adelaide.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Established in 1913, it is one of Australia's longest running providers of community-based adult learning.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] WEA-SA delivers short courses, lectures, cultural programs, travel and interest clubs designed to promote lifelong learning.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] StudyAdelaide, a collaboration between the South Australian government and the tertiary education sector, maintains an on-line list of schools, universities, and higher education institutions in SA.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In addition to the universities, Adelaide is home to research institutes, including the Royal Institution of Australia, established in 2009 as a counterpart to the two-hundred-year-old Royal Institution of Great Britain.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] While established as a British province, and very much English in terms of its culture, Adelaide attracted immigrants from other parts of Europe early on, including German and other European non-conformists escaping religious persecution.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The first German Lutherans arrived in 1838, bringing with them the vine cuttings that they used to found the acclaimed wineries of the Barossa Valley.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Royal Adelaide Show is an annual agricultural show and state fair, established in 1839 and now a huge event held in the Adelaide Showground annually.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's arts scene flourished in the 1960s and 1970s with the support of successive premiers from both major political parties.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The renowned Adelaide Festival of Arts was established in 1960 under Thomas Playford, which in the same year spawned an unofficial uncurated series of performances and exhibits which grew into the Adelaide Fringe.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Construction of the Adelaide Festival Centre began under Steele Hall in 1970 and was completed under the subsequent government of Don Dunstan, who also established the South Australian Film Corporation in 1972 and the State Opera of South Australia in 1976.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] With the Festival, the Fringe, WOMADelaide, Writers' Week and the Adelaide 500 street motor racing event (along with evening music concerts) all happening in early March, the period became known colloquially as "Mad March".
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2014, Ghil'ad Zuckermann founded the Adelaide Language Festival.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] There are many international cultural fairs, most notably the German Schützenfest and Greek Glendi.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide holds an annual Christmas pageant, the world's largest Christmas parade.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] As the state capital, Adelaide has a great number of cultural institutions, many of them along the boulevard of North Terrace.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Art Gallery of South Australia, with about 35,000 works, holds Australia's second largest state-based collection.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adjacent are the South Australian Museum and State Library of South Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Botanic Garden, National Wine Centre and Tandanya National Aboriginal Cultural Institute are nearby in the East End of the city.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In the back of the State Library lies the Migration Museum, Australia's oldest museum of its kind.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Further west, the Lion Arts Centre is home to ACE Open, which showcases contemporary art; Dance Hub SA; and other studios and arts industry spaces.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Mercury Cinema and the JamFactory ceramics and design gallery are just around the corner.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Festival Centre (which includes the Dunstan Playhouse, Festival Theatre and Space Theatre), on the banks of the Torrens, is the focal point for much of the cultural activity in the city and home to the State Theatre Company of South Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Other live music and theatre venues include the Adelaide Entertainment Centre; Adelaide Oval; Memorial Drive Park; Thebarton Theatre; Adelaide Town Hall; Her Majesty's Theatre; Queen's Theatre; Holden Street Theatres; and the Hopgood Theatre.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Lion Arts Factory, within the Lion Arts Centre, hosts contemporary music in a wide range of genres, as does "The Gov" in Hindmarsh.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The city also has numerous smaller theatres, pubs and cabaret bars which host performances.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2015, it was said that there were now more live music venues per capita in Adelaide than any other capital city in the southern hemisphere, *Lonely Planet* labelled Adelaide "Australia's live music city", and the city was recognised as a "City of Music" by the UNESCO Creative Cities Network.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Although there were many pubs hosting live music in the CBD in past, the number has slowly diminished.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Grace Emily on Waymouth Street, which was refurbished as a live music venue around 2000, is popular with musicians and patrons alike.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Crown & Anchor ("the Cranker") was saved from demolition in 2024 after a vigorous campaign by the public as well as many musicians and politicians.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] New legislation passed on 11 September 2024 designates the entire Adelaide CBD as a "live music venue area", and gives protection to selected live music venues.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In addition to its own WOMAD (WOMADelaide), Adelaide has attracted several touring music festivals, including Creamfields, Laneway, and Groovin' (some since defunct).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has produced musical groups and individuals who have achieved national and international fame.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Noted rocker Jimmy Barnes (formerly lead vocalist with Cold Chisel) spent most of his youth in the northern suburb of Elizabeth.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Australian singer-songwriter Paul Kelly grew up in Adelaide and was head prefect at Rostrevor College.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The first *Australian Idol* winner, Guy Sebastian, hails from the north-eastern suburb of Golden Grove.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] All of the five Australian national television networks broadcast both high-definition digital and standard-definition digital television services in Adelaide.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] They share three transmission towers on the ridge near the summit of Mount Lofty.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] There are two other transmission sites at 25 Grenfell Street, Adelaide and Elizabeth Downs.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The two government-funded stations are run by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC South Australia) and the Special Broadcasting Service (SBS).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Seven Network and Network Ten both own their Adelaide stations (SAS-7 and ADS-10 respectively).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's NWS-9 is part of the Nine Network.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide also has a community television station, Channel 44.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] As part of a nationwide phase-out of analogue television in Australia, Adelaide's analogue television service was shut down on 2 April 2013.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] There are 20 radio stations that serve the metropolitan area, as well as four stations that serve only parts of the metropolitan area; six commercial stations, six community stations, six national stations and two narrowcast stations.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] DAB+ digital radio has been broadcasting in metropolitan Adelaide since 20 May 2009, and currently offers a choice of 41 stations all operated by the existing licensed radio broadcasters, which includes high-quality simulcast of all AM and FM stations.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The main sports played professionally in Adelaide are Australian Rules football, soccer, cricket, netball, and basketball.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is the home of two Australian Football League teams: the Adelaide Football Club and Port Adelaide Football Club, and one A-League soccer team, Adelaide United.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] A local Australian rules football league, the South Australian National Football League (SANFL), is made up of 10 teams from around Adelaide.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The SANFL has been in operation since 1877 when it began as the South Australian Football Association (SAFA) before changing its name to the SANFL in 1927.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The SANFL is the oldest surviving football league of any code played in Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Since completion of the upgrade, home games for Adelaide Crows and Port Adelaide now take place at Adelaide Oval.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Since 1884, Adelaide Oval has also hosted an international cricket test every summer, along with a number of One Day International cricket matches.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Memorial Drive Park, adjacent to the Adelaide Oval, used to host Davis Cup and other major tennis events, including the Australian Open and the Adelaide International.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's professional association football team, Adelaide United, play in the A-League.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Founded in 2003, their home ground is Coopers Stadium, which has a capacity of 16,500 and is one of the few purpose-built soccer stadia in Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Prior to United's foundation, Adelaide City and West Adelaide represented the city in the National Soccer League.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The two sides, which contest the Adelaide derby against one another, now play in the National Premier Leagues South Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] For two years, 1997 and 1998, Adelaide was represented in Australia's top level rugby league, after the New South Wales Rugby League had played a single game per season at the Adelaide Oval for five years starting in 1991.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Rams were formed and played in the breakaway Super League (SL) competition in 1997 before moving to the new National Rugby League in 1998.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Initially playing at the Adelaide Oval, the club moved to the more suitable Hindmarsh Stadium late in the 1998 season.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] As part of a peace deal with the Australian Rugby League to end the Super League war, the club's owners News Limited (who were also owners of the SL) suddenly closed the club only weeks before the start of the 1999 season.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has two professional basketball teams, the men's team being the Adelaide 36ers which plays in the National Basketball League (NBL) and the women's team, the Adelaide Lightning which plays in the Women's National Basketball League (WNBL).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide 36ers play at the Adelaide Entertainment Centre while the Adelaide Lightning play at the Adelaide Arena (Previously Titanium Security Arena).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has a professional netball team, the Adelaide Thunderbirds, which plays in the national netball competition, the Super Netball championship, with home games played at Netball SA Stadium.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Thunderbirds occasionally play games or finals at the Titanium Security Arena, while international netball matches are usually played at the 10,500 seat Adelaide Entertainment Centre.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Titanium Security Arena has a capacity of 8,000 and is the largest purpose-built basketball stadium in Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Since 1999 Adelaide and its surrounding areas have hosted the Tour Down Under bicycle race, organised and directed by Adelaide-based Michael Turtur.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Turtur won an Olympic gold medal for Australia in the 4000 m team pursuit at the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Tour Down Under is the largest cycling event outside Europe and was the first event outside Europe to be granted UCI ProTour status.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The 2024 Women's Tour Down Under cycle stage race was held in and around Adelaide, South Australia from 12 to 14 January 2024.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide maintains a franchise in the Australian Baseball League, the Adelaide Giants.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] They have been playing since 2009, and their home stadium (until 2016) was Norwood Oval.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] From 2016 the team moved to the Diamond Sports Stadium located near the Adelaide International Airport due to renovations at Norwood.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide also has an ice hockey team, Adelaide Adrenaline in the Australian Ice Hockey League (AIHL).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] It was national champions in 2009 and plays its games at the IceArenA.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Australian Grand Prix for World Championship Formula One racing was hosted by Adelaide from 1985 to 1995 on the Adelaide Street Circuit which was laid out in the city's East End as well as the eastern parklands including the Victoria Park Racecourse.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Grand Prix became a source of pride, and losing the event to Melbourne in a surprise announcement in mid-1993 left a void that has since been filled with the Adelaide 500 for V8 Supercar racing, held on a modified version of the same street circuit.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Classic Adelaide, a rally of classic sporting vehicles, is also held in the city and its surrounds.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide formerly had three horse racing venues.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Victoria Park, Cheltenham Park Racecourse, both of which have now closed, and Morphettville Racecourse that remains the home of the South Australian Jockey Club.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] It also has Globe Derby Park for Harness racing that opened in 1969, and by 1973 had become Adelaide's premier harness racing venue taking over from the Wayville Showgrounds, as well as Greyhound Park for greyhound racing that opened in 1972.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The World Solar Challenge race attracts teams from around the world, most of which are fielded by universities or corporations, although some are fielded by high schools.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The race has a 20-years' history spanning nine races, with the inaugural event taking place in 1987.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide hosted the 2012 World Bowls Championships at Lockleys Bowling Club, becoming the third city in the world to have held the championships twice, having previously hosted the event in 1996.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Dirt track speedway is also popular in Adelaide with three operating speedways.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide Motorsport Park, located adjacent to the Adelaide International Raceway road racing circuit at Virginia (24 km (15 mi) north of the city centre) has been in continuous operation since 1979 after the closure of the popular Rowley Park Speedway.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Gillman Speedway located in the semi-industrial suburb of Gillman, has been in operation since 1998 and caters to Motorcycle speedway and Sidecars, while the Sidewinders Speedway located in Wingfield is also a motorcycle speedway dedicated to Under-16 riders and has been in operation since 1978.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2016, backed by South Australia's Peregrine Corporation opened up a multi-purpose facility; a state-of-the-art motorsporting park and a hotel alongside its newer OTR service station outside a small township of Tailem Bend currently named The Bend Motorsport Park.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Design for thrill seekers and rev-heads the facility currently host South Australia's second Supercars motoring event during a round in August.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is home to the Great Southern Slam, the world's largest roller derby tournament.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The tournament has been held biennially over Australia's Queen's Birthday holiday weekend since 2010.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2014, and 2016 the tournament featured 45 teams playing in two divisions.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2018, the tournament has expanded to 48 teams competing in three divisions.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Being centrally located on the Australian mainland, Adelaide forms a strategic transport hub for east–west and north–south routes.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The city itself has a metropolitan public transport system managed by and known as the Adelaide Metro.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Tramways were largely dismantled in the 1950s, but saw a revival in the 2010s with upgrades and extensions.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Road transport in Adelaide has historically been easier than many of the other Australian cities, with a well-defined city layout and wide multiple-lane roads from the beginning of its development.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide was known as a "twenty-minute city", with commuters having been able to travel from metropolitan outskirts to the city proper in roughly twenty minutes.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] However, such arterial roads often experience traffic congestion as the city grows.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide metropolitan area has one freeway and four expressways.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide metropolitan area has two commercial airports, Adelaide Airport and Parafield Airport.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide Airport, in Adelaide's south-western suburbs, serves almost 9 million passengers annually, with an extensive number of direct flight routes within Australia, as well as other destinations in Oceania, Asia and North America.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Parafield Airport, Adelaide's second airport 18 kilometres (11 miles) north of the city centre, is used for small aircraft, pilot training and recreational aviation purposes.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Parafield Airport served as Adelaide's main aerodrome until the opening of the Adelaide Airport in February 1955.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is also home to a military airport, known as RAAF Base Edinburgh, located in the northern suburbs.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] It was built in 1955 in a joint initiative with the United Kingdom for weapon development.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's two largest hospitals are the Royal Adelaide Hospital (RAH) in Adelaide Parklands, a teaching hospital affiliated with the University of Adelaide (800 beds), and the Flinders Medical Centre (580 beds) at Bedford Park, affiliated with Flinders University.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The RAH also operates additional campuses for specialist care throughout the suburbs including the Hampstead Rehabilitation Centre (150 beds) at Northfield and the Glenside Campus (129 beds) for acute mental health services.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Other major public hospitals are the Women's and Children's Hospital (305 beds), at North Adelaide; the Queen Elizabeth Hospital (340 beds) at Woodville; Modbury Hospital (174 beds) at Modbury; and the Lyell McEwin Hospital (198 beds) at Elizabeth Vale.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Numerous private hospitals are also located throughout the city, with the largest operators being not-for-profits Adelaide Community Healthcare Alliance (three hospitals) and Calvary Care (four hospitals).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2017, the RAH was relocated from the city's East End to a new AU$2.3 billion facility built over former railyards in the West End.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] SAHMRI, with additional external funding, has built a $300 million second facility completed in 2024, which was intended to house the Australian Bragg Centre with Australia's first proton therapy unit.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Construction is underway for the Women's and Children's Hospital to be relocated to the precinct adjacent the RAH by 2030.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The largest provider of community health care within Adelaide is the not-for-profit Royal District Nursing Service, which provides out of hospital care and hospital avoidance care.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's energy requirements were originally met by the Adelaide Electric Supply Company, which was nationalised by the Playford government in 1946, becoming the Electricity Trust of South Australia (ETSA).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The electricity retail market was opened to competition in 2003 and although competition was expected to result in lower retail costs, prices increased by 23.7% in the market's first year.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2004, the privatisation was deemed to be a failure with consumers paying 60% more for their power and with the state government estimated to lose $3 billion in power generation net income in the first ten years of privatisation.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2012, the industry came under scrutiny for allegedly reducing supply by shutting down generators during periods of peak demand to force prices up.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Increased media attention also revealed that in 2009 the state government had approved a 46% increase in retail prices to cover expected increases in the costs of generation while generation costs had in fact fallen 35% by 2012.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] South Australia has the highest retail price for electricity in the country.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Privatisation led to competition from a variety of companies who now separately provide for the generation, transmission, distribution and retail sales of gas and electricity.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Electricity generation comes from a range of technologies and operators.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] ElectraNet operates the high-voltage electricity transmission network.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] SA Power Networks distributes electricity to end users.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The largest electricity and gas retailing companies are also the largest generating companies.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The largest fossil fuel power stations are the Torrens Island Power Station gas-fired plant operated by AGL Energy and the Pelican Point Power Station operated by Engie.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] South Australia also has wind and solar power and connections to the national grid.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Gas is supplied from the Moomba Gas Processing Plant in the Cooper Basin via the Moomba Adelaide Pipeline System and the SEAGas pipeline from Victoria.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2011, South Australia generated 18% of its electricity from wind power, and had 51% of the installed capacity of wind generators in Australia.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Due to almost universal blackouts within the city during September 2016, the state worked with Tesla to produce the world's largest electricity battery at Hornsdale Power Reserve which has increased that state's electrical security to the extent in which large blackouts are no longer an event.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The provision of water services is by the government-owned SA Water.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's water is supplied from its seven reservoirs: Mount Bold, Happy Valley, Myponga, Millbrook, Hope Valley, Little Para and South Para.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The yield from these reservoir catchments can be as little as 10% of the city's requirements (90GL per annum) in drought years and about 60% in average years.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The remaining demand is met by the pumping of water from the River Murray.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] A sea-water desalination plant capable of supplying 100GL per annum was built during the 2001–2009 drought; however, it operated at about 8% of its capacity until 2019.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In December 2018, the State and Federal Governments agreed to fund a $2m study to determine how the plant could be used to reduce reliance on river water, in an effort to help save the Murray River basin and mouth (including the Coorong) from further ecological damage.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] AdelaideFree WiFi is a citywide free Wi-Fi network covering most of the inner city areas of Adelaide, primarily the Adelaide CBD and Northern Adelaide precincts.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] It was officially launched at the Adelaide Central Markets on Tuesday 25 June 2014.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] It was originally provided by Internode with infrastructure provided by outdoor Cisco WiFi N access points attached to the top of lighting poles, as well as inside cafes and businesses across the city.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2023, a new agreement was reached between the City of Adelaide and TPG Telecom to replace the network infrastructure, improving network speed and coverage.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The City of Adelaide, was a 10 sail composite (timber planking on a wrought-iron frame) clipper.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] It was rescued from the mooring where it sank, as HMS Carrick, in Glasgow in 1991.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] In 2001 it was decided that the ship's name would be reverted to the City of Adelaide, formally renamed in 2013, and arrived in Port Adelaide on 3 February 2014.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] It was not until June 2024 that the ship was moved from the barge Bradley by Wallbridge Gilbert Aztec (WGA) to the current home on Dock 2, as the centerpiece of a planned village in Port Adelaide's inner harbour.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The ship is owned by the Clipper Ship City of Adelaide Ltd (CSCOAL).
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The STV One and All, a 42-metre two-masted square-rigged brigantine and the ketch *The Failie* are moored at McLaren Wharf.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] The City of Adelaide has been involved in the sister cities movement since 1972.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] As of 2023 it has long-term international partnership arrangements with five cities, known as sister cities, based on formal agreements between Adelaide and each city.
[src:ambassador-clipper/adelaide-p02] This allows collaboration in the cultural, educational, business, and technical spheres.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Captain **Alfred Bulltop Stormalong** was an American folk hero and the subject of numerous nautical-themed tall tales originating in Massachusetts.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was said to be a sailor and a giant, some 30 feet (9.1 m) tall; he was the master of a huge clipper ship known in various sources as either the *Courser* or the *Tuscarora*, a ship purportedly so tall that it had hinged masts to avoid catching on the Moon.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The name of Stormalong first appeared in a cycle of sea shanties that Stan Hugill, in his *Sea Shanties of the Seven Seas*, traces back to African-American folk songs of the 1830s and '40s.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Bearing names like "Mister Stormalong", "Way Stormalong John", and "Yankee John, Stormalong", these sailors' work songs generally featured praise for a deceased seaman and for his benevolent son.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The tall tales about Stormalong first appeared in the 1911 book *Here's Audacity!* by Frank Shay.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] More tales appeared in the 1933 pamphlet *Old Stormalong Yarns* by C.E.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] New England was where he was beached as a baby, already three fathoms (18 ft) tall.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] According to one telling, he outgrew Cape Cod and moved to Boston, where he signed aboard the first ship that would take him at the age of twelve.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] He had a lifelong rivalry with a Kraken, a huge sea monster from Norse myth; in fact, the Kraken escaped from him in their first encounter, causing a dejected Stormalong to abandon the sea life for life as a farmer somewhere in the Midwest.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Some sources say he had a ship so large that a stable of Arabian horses were aboard for his crew to get from one end of the ship to the other.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Among other things, the ship Alfred was best said to have drilled the course of the Panama Canal by slamming into the Panamanian coast, and to have gotten stuck in the English Channel, which required the crew to grease the ship's hull with soap.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The soap combined with the scraping of the hull against the Gray Cliffs of Dover turned them bright white.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] As Stormalong grew older, he eventually encountered the Kraken again, this time successfully drawing the beast into a whirlpool from which it never escaped.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The aged Stormalong won the race by several miles, but the stress of handling the wheel through the difficult Atlantic crossing killed him.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was buried at sea, and Davy Jones himself opened his famous locker to accept Stormalong's body.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Another ending to his life is as follows: While Stormalong was on his Caribbean adventures, he passed by Florida, seeing that there was a tremendous hurricane that tore through his ship.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Ships sailing nearby were being tossed around by the heavy waves.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong went overboard and piled as many boats as he could onto his ship.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] When the storm finally wound down, the sailors were dropped back off at Florida.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] After that, he went back on board, unfurling the sails of his ship, seeing if they could be repaired.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A great wind, the last blow of the hurricane, hit the sails, lifting Stormalong and his ship into the sky.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A third ending to his life takes advantage of the inference that, being a giant, Alfred Bulltop Stormalong was an enormous eater.
[src:ambassador-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] It describes a time when his hunger was greater than usual and led him to eat so much food (one variant cites a breakfast of six sharks; it is not definitely known what other variants exist) that he suffered terminal indigestion, causing his magnificent appetite to finish him.
[src:ambassador-clipper/ambassador-clipper] William Walker built *Ambassador* at Lavender Dry Dock in London.
[src:ambassador-clipper/ambassador-clipper] Though considered a fast ship, *Ambassador* was said to be "very cranky and overmasted".
[src:ambassador-clipper/ambassador-clipper] Her first passage to the UK from Fuzhou came during the Tea Race of 1870 under Captain Duggan and took 115 days, a mediocre performance; that same year the fastest tea passage, also from Fuzhou, was made by the clipper *Lahloo* in just 98 days.
[src:ambassador-clipper/ambassador-clipper] *Ambassador*'s fastest passage between China and England was 108 days, in 1872.
[src:ambassador-clipper/ambassador-clipper] The wreck is now reduced to a skeletal frame.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The ***Andrew Jackson*** was a 1,679-registered-ton medium clipper built by the firm of Irons & Grinnell in Mystic, Connecticut in 1855.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The vessel was designed for the shipping firm of J.H.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Brower & Co. to carry cargo intended for sale to participants in the California Gold Rush.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The ship was 220 feet (67 m) in length, had a beam of 41 ft., 2 in., and a draft 22 ft., 3 in.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The vessel was described as "a very handsome, well-designed ship.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] This was one of only three 89-day runs performed by square-rigged ships driving from New York City to California.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The other two runs were both posted by *Flying Cloud*.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] *Flying Cloud*'s fastest New York-to-California run had taken 89 days and 8 hours; *Andrew Jackson*'s run was, by four hours, widely acclaimed in the newspapers as the fastest in history.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Some clipper ship authorities, including Howe and Matthews, assert that *Andrew Jackson* did not actually set the record described above.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] They concede, however, that this medium clipper, perhaps not naturally as fast as *Flying Cloud*, achieved a remarkable passage as the result of a combination of hard driving by the captain and favorable winds.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] However, after careful scrutiny of the logbooks, one author, Carl C.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Cutler, concludes that a case can be made for either *Flying Cloud* or *Andrew Jackson* holding the record.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Some will consider the passage from pilot-to-pilot as the appropriate indicator of fastest sailing performance around Cape Horn.
[src:ambassador-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] *Flying Cloud* holds the record time for a passage anchor-to-anchor from New York to San Francisco, of 89 days 8 hours, while *Andrew Jackson'*s completed passage anchor-to-anchor may have been as long as 89 days 20 hours.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] The schooner ***Anglona*** was the first American opium clipper.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] She sailed in the Chinese coastal trade in the 1840s, and had a famous race with the schooner *Ariel* around Lintin Island.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] Forbes was interested in fast schooners for clipper and coastal service in China.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] The first clipper which Forbes sent to China, the *Rose*, foundered in the July typhoon of 1841.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] Forbes purchased *Anglona* at Brown & Bell's New York yard for Russell & Co. for use as a despatch boat between Hong Kong, Macao, and Whampoa.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] Other American pilot boat models sent to China in the 1840s included the *Zephyr* and the *Spec*, also built on the New York model.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] Shortly after Shanghai opened to foreign trade, three Boston pilot boats were sent: the 90 ton *Golden Gate*, the 90 ton *Siren*, and the 75 ton *Daniel Webster*, which served as pilot boats in the Yangtze River.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] Within two weeks of purchase, *Anglona* sailed for China under Captain Turner.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] She arrived at Cape Horn in 61 days, and Java Head in 95 days.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] Russell & Co put *Anglona* in service on the Canton River until the new treaty ports opened, at which time she was put in the coastal trade.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] Captain Turner did not serve long, as he was knocked overboard by the mainboom during a sudden jibe, and drowned.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] In 1843, *Anglona* was under command of Capt.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] Adamson; in 1844 she was under Captain Macfarlane.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] On September 20, 1841, *Anglona* left Hong Kong with a 108-ton cargo of rice from Macao bound for the East Coast; on Dec.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] 2, she left Hong Kong with a 108-ton cargo from Macao of opium or specie bound for Namoa.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] Lee, the designer of the *Rose*, wanted to know why Forbes hadn't come to him for a clipper schooner instead, and got Forbes to agree to taking a half interest in one of his schooners if it could beat the *Anglona*.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] The *Ariel*, a new 92-ton schooner built by Sprague & James at Medford, MA was taken out for a trial in 1841 out of Lewis Wharf in Boston Harbor, against the 30 ton schooner-yacht *Breeze*, which had been built for Forbes by Daniel C.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] The wind had freshened and was blowing in hard puffs.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] He had suggested taking in a second reef, but his companions assured him the wind would slacken as they approached the harbor.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] In stays off Sound Point Beacon, the Ariel laid down before she could get way on for a tack towards Long Island, and sank in seven fathoms of water.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] When *Ariel* was refloated, Lee agreed to reduce the rig, and cut down the masts as per Forbes’ suggestion.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] *Ariel* was then sent to China under Capt.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] Poor, making an 80-day passage to Anjer.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] The race between *Ariel* and *Anglona* was about 40 mi., from Macao Roads around Lintin and back, for stakes of $1,000 and Forbes’ agreement to take half-interest in *Ariel* if she won.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] *Anglona* was much stronger sailing to windward, due to the shallow draft of *Ariel,* and took the lead until rounding the island.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] At that point, *Ariel* set a large flying square sail and topsail.
[src:ambassador-clipper/anglona-clipper] *Anglona* had no ballooning sails for running downwind, and was beaten by 17 minutes.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] The hull was black, the inside dark buff with blue waterways.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] In 1853, *Antelope* arrived in San Francisco from New York under Captain Snow on August 31 after a passage of 128 days, returning to New York via Callao in 178 days.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] After one more round trip to the West Coast of South America *Antelope* went into the China trade.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] In July 1858, *Antelope* departed Bangkok for China under Captain Clarke.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] On August 6, she struck on Discovery Shoal, Paracels Reef, which was not visible due to a high, ending her sailing career after six years and nine months.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Captain Clarke, four passengers, and 13 seamen abandoned ship, and set out in one of the ship's boats.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] A second boat, which became separated during the night, carried the mate, one seaman, and ten Chinese passengers.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Four days later, a Chinese fishing junk came into view.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Clarke offered the fishermen $20 for a tow to a place where water could be had.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Once the *Antelope* party was taken in tow, it became evident that the fishermen were not trustworthy.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Fearing piracy, the shipwrecked party cut the tow rope and attempted an escape.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] The fishermen pursued the boat, attacked it with stones, and finally set two fishermen to stand guard with spears while the others robbed the *Antelope* party.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] In the midst of the confusion, two of the *Antelope* sailors took advantage of the distraction and boarded the fishing junk, dispatching its crew.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Captain Clarke also attempted to board the junk, but fell in the water and had to be rescued.
[src:ambassador-clipper/antelope-of-boston] The shipwrecked *Antelope* party then took command of the junk, and arrived in Hong Kong on August 14.
[src:ambassador-clipper/ariel-clipper] A premium was paid for the first consignment of tea to reach London in each season.
[src:ambassador-clipper/ariel-clipper] The clipper *Fiery Cross* left Fuzhou on 29 May and *Ariel*, *Taeping* and *Serica* on the 30th.
[src:ambassador-clipper/ariel-clipper] On 6 September *Taeping* docked twenty minutes ahead of *Ariel*, and about two hours ahead of *Serica*.
[src:ambassador-clipper/ariel-clipper] *Fiery Cross* and *Taitsing* arrived two days later.
[src:ambassador-clipper/ariel-clipper] After 99 days and almost 16,000 miles (26,000 km) the leaders were still tied and raced within sight of each other the full length of the English Channel and into the Thames.
[src:ambassador-clipper/ariel-clipper] *Taeping*, under Captain McKinnon, drew less water and was able to tie up in the London docks twenty minutes ahead of *Ariel*, under Captain Keay.
[src:ambassador-clipper/ariel-clipper] *Taeping* divided her winnings of 10 shillings per ton with the owners of *Ariel* and Captain McKinnon divided the captain's £100 with Captain Keay, who hailed from Anstruther.
[src:ambassador-clipper/ariel-clipper] With the completion of the Suez Canal the tea trade was taken over by steamships and most of the clippers transferred to the Australian trade, carrying general cargo to either Sydney or Melbourne, and returning with wool — for which a premium price was also paid on the first shipments of the season.
[src:ambassador-clipper/bald-eagle-clipper] The *Bald Eagle'*s voyages are listed here.
[src:ambassador-clipper/bald-eagle-clipper] Sources disagree on some departure and arrival dates and passage lengths; disagreements or ambiguities are individually cited.
[src:ambassador-clipper/bald-eagle-clipper] City names are entered as spelled at the time.
[src:ambassador-clipper/bald-eagle-clipper] Although Basil Lubbock wrote an account that in October 1861 *Bald Eagle* came under attack by Chinese pirates while en route to Peru with a cargo of Chinese laborers, was put on fire, and then abandoned at sea some 500 miles east of Manila, there is little evidence to support his account.
[src:ambassador-clipper/bald-eagle-clipper] Richard McKay calls it a "fake yarn" and cites F.
[src:ambassador-clipper/bald-eagle-clipper] Matthews, a "well-known authority of ships...of the past" that *Bald Eagle* sailed from Hong Kong for San Francisco with a cargo including rice, sugar, tea, and "treasure" and was never heard of again.
